'''Kirsten Bakis''' (born 1967 Switzerland) is an American [[novelist]].<ref>{{cite book |title= The Chronology of American Literature |last= Burt|first= Daniel S. (editor)|authorlink= |year= c. 2004|publisher= Houghton Mifflin|location= |isbn= 0-618-16821-4|page= 716 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VQ0fgo5v6e0C&pg=PA716&dq=Kirsten+Bakis&cd=7#v=onepage&q=Kirsten%20Bakis&f=false|accessdate= May 16, 2010}}</ref>
==Life== Bakis was raised in [[Westchester County, New York]], and graduated from [[New York University]] in 1990. She is a recipient of a Teaching/Writing Fellowship from the [[University of Iowa]] [[Iowa Writers' Workshop|Writer's Workshop]], a grant from the Michener/Copernicus Society of America.
She has taught at [[Hampshire College]] and was a writer-in-residence at [[Skidmore College]], [[Saratoga Springs]], New York in 2005. She is currently living in Croton-on-Hudson, New York with her husband, their two children, and two dogs, and is at work on her second novel.
==Critical reception== ''Lives of the Monster Dogs'' received mostly positive reviews. Critics praised it for its originality, while also noting some of its drawbacks as science fiction.<ref>"Kirsten Bakis." Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2005. Literature Resource Center. Web. 10 June 2014.</ref>
==Awards== * 2004 [[Whiting Awards|Whiting Award]] for fiction * New York Times Notable Book for the year, for ''Lives of the Monster Dogs'' * [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] shortlisted, for ''Lives of the Monster Dogs'' * [[Bram Stoker Award for Best First Novel]], for ''Lives of the Monster Dogs''
