{{Infobox university |name = University of Ez-Zitouna |image = <!-- Missing image removed: [[File:Ezzitouna University.gif|University of Ez-Zitouna Logo]] --> |motto = |established = 737 (120 [[anno hegirae|A.H]]) |type = [[Public university]] |vice_chancellor= Salem Bouyahia (President) |undergrad = 1200 |postgrad = 350 |faculty = 90 |staff = |city = [[Tunis]] |country = [[Tunisia]] |campus = |free_label = |free = |website= [http://www.uz.rnu.tn/en/ www.uz.rnu.tn] }}
[[File:PatioDarSoulaimania.JPG|thumb|University of Ez-Zitouna]] '''Ez-Zitouna University''' ({{lang-ar|جامعة الزيتونة}}, {{lang-fr|Université Zitouna}}) is in Montfleury, [[Tunis]]. It was first established in 737 and subsequently modernised in 1956. It consists of the Higher Institute of Theology and the Higher Institute of Islamic Civilisation in Tunis and a research institution, the Center of Islamic Studies, in [[Kairouan]].
==History== For centuries, [[Kairouan|Qirwan]] was the early centre of learning and intellectual pursuits in Tunisia and [[North Africa]] in General. Starting from the 13th century, Tunis became the capital of [[Ifriqiya]] under [[Almohad]] and [[Hafsid]] rule.<ref name="ref-23">{{Cite journal | first= Mary J. | last=Deeb | title=Ez-Zituna; op cit; | pages= 374}}</ref> This shift in power helped Ez-Zitouna to flourish and become one of the major centres of Islamic learning, and [[Ibn Khaldun]], the first social historian in history was one of its products.<ref name="ref-24">{{cite journal | author = Charnay, Jean-Paul | title=Economy and Religion in the Works of Ibn Khaldun | journal = the Maghreb Review | volume = 4 #1 | pages=1–25 | date = January–February 1979}}</ref> The flourishing university attracted students and men of learning from all parts of the known world at the time. Along with [[theology]]; mainly the [[Qur'an]], the university taught [[jurisprudence]], [[history]], [[grammar]], [[science]] and [[medicine]].<ref name="ref-23"/> When it comes to books and libraries, Ez-Zituna libraries were the richest among North African counterparts. It had several collections totaling in the tens of thousands of books. One of its libraries, el-Abdaliyah included a large collection of rare and unique manuscripts.<ref name="ox-ency"> {{cite encyclopaedia | title = Ez-Zituna | encyclopaedia = The Oxford Encyclopaedia of the Modern Islamic World | volume=4 | pages=374 | publisher = Oxford The oldest university in the world Press | year=1995 | author = M.J. Deeb | editor = J.L. Esposito}} </ref> The manuscripts covered almost all subjects and sciences, including grammar, [[logic]], [[documentations]], etiquette of research, [[cosmology]], [[arithmetic]], [[geometry]], [[minerals]], [[vocational training]], etc.<ref name="hafez"> {{cite book | last = Abd el-Hafiz | first = Mansour | title = Fihris Makhtutat el-Maktaba al- Ahmadiya bi Tunis | publisher = Dar el-Fat'h | location = Beirut | year = 1969 | pages = 8&ndash;9 }} </ref><ref name="mosques-libraries"> {{cite book | last = Sibai | first = M. | title = Mosque Libraries : An Historical Study | publisher = Mansell Publishing Limited | location = London and New York | year = 1987 | pages=98}} </ref>
Historically the traditional pedagogy of the university opposed French influence in [[Culture of Tunisia|Tunisian culture]], even though younger people who studied there and who were unable to attend other universities lost the concept of the university having prestige. The students, faculty, and alumni became an integral part of the 1920s [[Destour]] party.<ref>Micaud 93.</ref>
Following [[Tunisian independence|Tunisia's Independence]], the modern Zitouna University was established on April 26, 1956. This was succeeded by the Zitouna Faculty of Shari’a and Theology on March 1, 1961 which became one of the components of Tunisian University. The Zitouna name was restored by [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]] in 1987, after having been changed under [[Habib Bourguiba|Bourguiba]].<ref>Paul Delaney, "New Tunis Chief Begins Democratic Changes," New York Times, December 13, 1987.</ref>
==Academics==
The present-day institution has some 1200 students and 90 faculty, divided between two associated institutes — the Higher Institute of Theology and the Higher Institute of Islamic Civiliation in Tunis — and a research institution, the Center of Islamic Studies ({{Lang-ar|مركز الدراسات الإسلامية بالقيروان}}) in [[Kairouan]].
Lessons in the Higher Institute of Theology began in the academic year 1988/89. It awards # Bachelor's degree in Shari'a and Islamic thought in Islamic Sciences # Master in Islamic Sciences # Ph.D. in Islamic Sciences # Superior Technician in Applied Multimedia on Islamic Arts # Superior Technician in Arts of Islamic Heritage
The Higher Institute of Islamic Civilisation has some 300 students and 40 researchers. It awards # National diploma of the first cycle in Islamic studies (D.E.U.P.C.) # National diploma of Masters in the Islamic studies
== Faculties == # Islamic studies and Islamic civilization # Islamic law # Theology
==Notable alumni== Famous alumni include the scholar [[Ibn Khaldun|Abdul-Rahman Ibn Khaldun]], the trade unionist and writer [[Tahar Haddad]], the politician and writer [[Abdelaziz Thâalbi]], and the Tunisian national poet [[Aboul-Qacem Echebbi]].
